english:
  title: The Tale of Gunjman, the Filial Performer
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Gunjman was the son of Gunja, an entertainer from Jinju. In the winter of the Hongwu era, his father was mauled by a tiger in the night. Gunjman cried out to heaven and waited for dawn, then took up bow and arrows and entered the mountains. The tiger had finished its meal but, seeing Gunjman, bared its fangs and lunged forward, spilling fragments of bone and sinew from its jaws. With a single arrow, Gunjman struck it dead. He drew his sword, split open the beast's belly, and gathered every remaining bone of his father. He burned them and gave them proper burial.

    At that same time, in the neighboring county of Gosung, there lived an elderly man with seven sons who fell gravely ill. A shaman declared that evil spirits had afflicted him and that he must be moved. The seven sons believed this counsel and had their father carried outside to sleep in the open air behind the house, where they lay circling him in vigil. In the dead of night, a tiger came and seized their father and dragged him away—yet all seven sons slept so soundly they heard nothing. Upon waking, they thought their father had returned to the house. They went inside to find him, only to discover he was gone. The seven sons were seized with panic, not knowing where to turn. By morning, a passerby arrived with news: "Last night, passing through a grove, I heard a man's voice crying out in terrible anguish." They hastened to search and found their father half-devoured, the tiger having fled with the other half untouched. Though gripped with fear, none of the seven sons pursued the beast. In the end they caught nothing, and returned home with only half their father's remains to bury.

    Alas! Gunjman, through strength of will alone, stood against the ferocity of that savage thing and avenged his father swiftly. Yet these seven sons, despite their great number, could not accomplish what he did. How strange that filial devotion—that cutting sorrow and urgent need to honor one's parent in the moment of loss—should manifest so differently in different hearts. Truly, this is cause for deepest lament.

    A historian writes: "The seven sons' failure in filial duty was not merely that they could not match Gunjman's deed. To provide comfort in living and attentive care in sickness is the natural obligation of a son to his parent. When an aged and ailing father lies upon his bed, one must faithfully prepare his medicine and ensure his warmth—yet instead these sons heeded a shaman's false words and left their father's weakened, disease-ridden body exposed to wind, frost, and bitter cold. This is their first sin.

    "When attending the ill, one must sleep fully clothed, without removing cap or sash. Yet these seven sons left their ailing father in a tiger's den and stretched out their limbs in blissful sleep, so deep they did not even hear the beast's assault. Where then was their concern? This is their second sin.

    "The classics say: 'In death's calamity, brothers embrace with depth of feeling'—for such bonds move the heart beyond all containment. If brothers feel thus toward one another, how much more toward a father? When they searched in desperation and could not find him, then saw his scattered remains and blood defiling the earth, grief seized them utterly. In such agony, they should have thought nothing of their own safety, but sought only to strike down the killer and deliver swift vengeance to ease their torment even slightly. Yet the seven sons merely hesitated, unchanging in their cowardice, and dared not act. This is their third sin.

    "Long ago, Huang Xiang, though but a woman, rode upon a tiger and saved her father's life. Yao-shi too, a mere woman, beat back a tiger and preserved her mother. What a woman could do, these seven sons could not. This is their fourth sin.

    "Even had all seven been weak and powerless, had they but wept and pleaded with their neighbors to join them, who would have refused? This is their fifth sin.

    "An entertainer knows only clever jesting; a scholar is bound by propriety. These seven claimed the title of gentlemen, yet proved inferior to one performer. This is their sixth sin.

    "To sustain life is not enough to accomplish great things; only in honoring the dead do we accomplish what is great. We choose the burial ground with care, that our parents may rest secure in the earth, and only then does our own heart find peace. Yet the seven sons buried only half their father's remains, abandoning the rest to the tiger's filth, uncollected and forgotten. How could their hearts ever know peace? This is their seventh sin.

    "A parent's killer and the child share no sky—that is the law. These sons failed to avenge their father while the moment lived; later, even should they catch the tiger, how would they know it took their father? Thus their vengeance remains forever impossible. This is their eighth sin.

    "When a parent's enemy lives, one sleeps upon sackcloth and keeps spear at hand, engaging in battle even in the marketplace—one never lays down arms until death. Yet the seven sons, though they do not know which tiger took their father, should nonetheless bear weapons always and seek to slay every tiger, maintaining this vigilance unto life's end. Did they do so? This is their ninth sin.

    "One who shows coldness toward those deserving warmth will show coldness to all. The seven sons showed coldness to those most deserving of warmth—how then could they show warmth to any? This is their tenth sin.

    "Of the three thousand kinds of punishment, none exceeds the crime of impiety. Truly, this is cause for lamentation. Yet Gunjman did more than slay the beast—when the tiger saw him, it spewed forth what it had consumed. Such is the power of sincere filial devotion! Even the savage creature could not digest its meal in peace, but seemed to surrender itself as though confessing guilt. Is he not all the more worthy?"

    Thus spoke the historian.
